            deepDive: "CJC-1295 is a synthetic, tetrasubstituted analog of Growth Hormone-Releasing Hormone (GHRH) with a Drug Affinity Complex (DAC) covalently attached to the C-terminus.\n\nThe DAC Technology: Invented by ConjuChem, the DAC is a reactive chemical group (usually a maleimide) that selectively and covalently binds to the free thiol group of cysteine-34 on endogenous serum albumin.\n\nPharmacokinetics: Because serum albumin is a massive protein that is not easily filtered by the kidneys and has a natural half-life of about 19 days, attaching the peptide to albumin protects it from enzymatic degradation and renal clearance. This extends the half-life to approximately 6-8 days.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\n1. Continuous Receptor Activation: The albumin-bound CJC-1295 circulates in the blood and continuously binds to GHRH receptors on the anterior pituitary.\n2. The 'Bleed' vs. The 'Pulse': Native GHRH is released in discrete pulses by the hypothalamus, allowing the pituitary receptors to reset. CJC-1295 DAC never leaves the receptor. This causes a continuous, low-level leakage of GH into the bloodstream (a 'bleed'), raising the trough (baseline) levels of GH rather than just the peak (pulse) levels.\n3. IGF-1 Accumulation: Because the liver is constantly bombarded with GH, it continuously produces IGF-1. Clinical trials showed that a single injection kept IGF-1 levels elevated above baseline for up to 28 days.\n\nThe Somatostatin Battle: Because CJC-1295 DAC is constantly trying to release GH, the body responds by constantly releasing Somatostatin to try and stop it. Stacking CJC-1295 DAC with a GHRP (which inhibits Somatostatin) breaks this stalemate.\n\nLong-Term Use Data: There is no long-term safety data for continuous GHRH receptor activation. The primary theoretical concerns are pituitary hyperplasia, receptor downregulation, and the metabolic consequences of chronic GH elevation (insulin resistance and acromegaly-like symptoms).",
            faq: [
                FAQItem(question: "Is 'With DAC' better for building muscle than 'No DAC'?", answer: "It will raise your overall IGF-1 levels higher and faster than 'No DAC', which theoretically leads to more muscle growth. However, the side effects (water retention, lethargy, insulin resistance) are significantly worse. Most advanced bodybuilders prefer 'No DAC' to avoid the bloat."),
                FAQItem(question: "Why do I feel so tired all the time on this?", answer: "Chronically elevated GH levels are known to cause profound lethargy. Your body is essentially in a constant state of repair and growth, which requires massive amounts of energy."),
                FAQItem(question: "Can I take it every day to get faster results?", answer: "NO. With an 8-day half-life, taking it every day will cause the drug to accumulate exponentially in your blood. You will experience severe carpal tunnel syndrome, massive edema, and potentially dangerous spikes in blood sugar. Once or twice a week is the absolute maximum."),
                FAQItem(question: "Will it shut down my natural GH production?", answer: "Unlike injecting synthetic HGH, CJC-1295 stimulates your pituitary to work harder. However, constantly stimulating it 24/7 for months on end can lead to 'pituitary fatigue,' where the gland becomes desensitized."),
                FAQItem(question: "Is the water weight permanent?", answer: "No. The water retention is a direct pharmacological effect of the elevated GH and aldosterone. Once you stop taking the peptide (which takes 2-3 weeks to clear), you will rapidly drop the water weight."),
            ],
            references: [
