            deepDive: "Ipamorelin is a synthetic pentapeptide (Aib-His-D-2-Nal-D-Phe-Lys-NH2). It is a selective agonist of the ghrelin/growth hormone secretagogue receptor (GHS-R1a).\n\nReceptor Binding: It binds specifically to the GHS-R1a receptor in the pituitary and hypothalamus.\n\nPharmacokinetics: It has a terminal half-life of approximately 2 hours, which is significantly longer than natural ghrelin or GHRP-6.\n\nSelectivity: Unlike other GHRPs, Ipamorelin is highly selective for GH release. It does not significantly stimulate the release of ACTH (which triggers cortisol) or prolactin, even at doses 200 times higher than the effective dose for GH release.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\nIpamorelin acts as a ghrelin mimetic. Binding to the GHS-R1a receptor activates the phospholipase C (PLC) and protein kinase C (PKC) intracellular pathways, leading to an influx of calcium ions. This triggers the immediate release of stored GH vesicles. Additionally, Ipamorelin acts as a functional antagonist to somatostatin (the hormone that inhibits GH release), effectively 'taking the foot off the brake' while simultaneously 'pressing the gas.'\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\nIpamorelin was extensively studied by Novo Nordisk in the 1990s. In human trials, it demonstrated a dose-dependent increase in GH release with an SC50 (concentration required for half-maximal stimulation) of 214 nmol/L. It was proven to be the first GHRP to not elevate cortisol or prolactin levels in humans, confirming its high selectivity.\n\nSynergy with GHRH: Ipamorelin (acting via PKC/calcium) and CJC-1295 (acting via cAMP/PKA) trigger GH release through completely different intracellular pathways. When used together, they produce a massive, synergistic GH pulse.\n\nLong-Term Use Data:\nBecause it does not elevate cortisol or prolactin, Ipamorelin is considered the safest GHRP for long-term use (12-16 week cycles).",
            faq: [
                FAQItem(question: "Why is Ipamorelin considered better than GHRP-6?", answer: "GHRP-6 causes intense, ravenous hunger and elevates cortisol and prolactin. Ipamorelin was specifically engineered to stimulate the exact same GH release without causing hunger or elevating stress hormones."),
                FAQItem(question: "Do I have to inject it with CJC-1295?", answer: "You don't have to, but you should. Taking Ipamorelin alone gives you a 2+2=4 effect. Taking it with CJC-1295 gives you a 2+2=10 effect due to their synergistic mechanisms."),
                FAQItem(question: "Will this make me gain a lot of muscle?", answer: "No. Peptides that stimulate natural GH release are excellent for recovery, sleep, and anti-aging, but they are not anabolic steroids. They will not cause massive muscle hypertrophy on their own."),
                FAQItem(question: "Why do I have to inject it on an empty stomach?", answer: "When you eat carbohydrates or fats, your body releases insulin and free fatty acids. These trigger the release of somatostatin, a hormone that acts like a 'stop' signal to your pituitary gland. If somatostatin is active, Ipamorelin cannot tell your pituitary to release growth hormone."),
                FAQItem(question: "Will Ipamorelin make me fail a drug test?", answer: "Yes. It is explicitly banned by WADA and most major sporting organizations under the category of peptide hormones and growth factors."),
