            deepDive: "GHRP-2 (Pralmorelin) is a synthetic hexapeptide (D-Ala-D-2-Nal-Ala-Trp-D-Phe-Lys-NH2). It is a potent agonist of the ghrelin/growth hormone secretagogue receptor (GHS-R1a).\n\nReceptor Binding: It binds specifically to the GHS-R1a receptor in the pituitary and hypothalamus.\n\nPharmacokinetics: It has a short terminal half-life of approximately 15 to 60 minutes following intravenous or subcutaneous administration.\n\nSelectivity: Unlike Ipamorelin, GHRP-2 is not perfectly selective. While its primary action is GH release, it also causes a statistically significant, dose-dependent increase in ACTH (leading to cortisol release) and prolactin.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\nGHRP-2 acts as a ghrelin mimetic. Binding to the GHS-R1a receptor activates the phospholipase C (PLC) and protein kinase C (PKC) intracellular pathways, leading to an influx of calcium ions. This triggers the immediate release of stored GH vesicles. It also acts as a functional antagonist to somatostatin. The mild hunger effect is mediated by its action on ghrelin receptors in the hypothalamus (specifically the arcuate nucleus), which stimulate NPY/AgRP neurons.\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\nGHRP-2 has been extensively studied in humans. In human trials, it demonstrated a massive, dose-dependent increase in GH release. It is considered slightly more potent than GHRP-6 in terms of peak GH release. Because of its reliability in stimulating GH, it was approved in Japan (as Pralmorelin) as a diagnostic agent to test for pituitary dwarfism and GH deficiency.\n\nSynergy with GHRH: GHRP-2 (acting via PKC/calcium) and CJC-1295 (acting via cAMP/PKA) trigger GH release through completely different intracellular pathways. When used together, they produce a massive, synergistic GH pulse.\n\nLong-Term Use Data:\nDue to its potential to elevate cortisol and prolactin, long-term uninterrupted use is generally discouraged compared to Ipamorelin. Cycles should be strictly limited to 12-16 weeks.",
            faq: [
                FAQItem(question: "Will GHRP-2 make me as hungry as GHRP-6?", answer: "No. While GHRP-6 is notorious for causing uncontrollable, ravenous hunger, GHRP-2 causes a much milder, more manageable increase in appetite."),
                FAQItem(question: "Why do I have to inject it on an empty stomach?", answer: "When you eat carbohydrates or fats, your body releases insulin and free fatty acids. These trigger the release of somatostatin, a hormone that acts like a 'stop' signal to your pituitary gland. If somatostatin is active, GHRP-2 cannot tell your pituitary to release growth hormone."),
                FAQItem(question: "Can I use GHRP-2 for fat loss?", answer: "Yes, the growth hormone released will aid in fat loss. However, because it stimulates appetite, you will need strong willpower to maintain a caloric deficit. If hunger is an issue, Ipamorelin is a better choice for fat loss."),
                FAQItem(question: "Do I have to inject it with CJC-1295?", answer: "You don't have to, but you should. Taking GHRP-2 alone gives you a 2+2=4 effect. Taking it with CJC-1295 gives you a 2+2=10 effect due to their synergistic mechanisms."),
                FAQItem(question: "Will GHRP-2 make me fail a drug test?", answer: "Yes. It is explicitly banned by WADA and most major sporting organizations under the category of peptide hormones and growth factors."),
