            deepDive: "GHRP-6 (Growth Hormone Releasing Hexapeptide) is a synthetic hexapeptide (His-D-Trp-Ala-Trp-D-Phe-Lys-NH2). It was one of the first synthetic ghrelin mimetics developed.\n\nReceptor Binding: It binds specifically to the GHS-R1a receptor in the pituitary and hypothalamus.\n\nPharmacokinetics: It has a distribution half-life of ~7.6 minutes and an elimination half-life of ~2.5 hours following subcutaneous administration.\n\nSelectivity: GHRP-6 is considered a 'dirty' peptide compared to newer generations. Alongside GH release, it causes a statistically significant, dose-dependent increase in ACTH (leading to cortisol release) and prolactin.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\nGHRP-6 acts as a ghrelin mimetic. Binding to the GHS-R1a receptor activates the phospholipase C (PLC) and protein kinase C (PKC) intracellular pathways, leading to an influx of calcium ions. This triggers the immediate release of stored GH vesicles. It also acts as a functional antagonist to somatostatin. The extreme hunger effect is mediated by its strong action on ghrelin receptors in the hypothalamus (specifically the arcuate nucleus), which heavily stimulate NPY/AgRP neurons.\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\nGHRP-6 has been extensively studied in humans since the 1990s. In human trials, it demonstrated a massive, dose-dependent increase in GH release. However, due to its side effect profile (hunger, cortisol, prolactin), pharmaceutical development largely shifted toward cleaner analogs like Ipamorelin or orally active non-peptide secretagogues (like MK-677).\n\nSynergy with GHRH: GHRP-6 (acting via PKC/calcium) and CJC-1295 (acting via cAMP/PKA) trigger GH release through completely different intracellular pathways. When used together, they produce a massive, synergistic GH pulse.\n\nLong-Term Use Data:\nDue to its potential to elevate cortisol and prolactin, and its tendency to cause significant water retention, long-term uninterrupted use is strongly discouraged. Cycles should be strictly limited to 12-16 weeks, and it is generally only used for specific bulking phases.",
