            deepDive: "Tirzepatide is a 39-amino acid synthetic peptide. It is an analog of the human GIP (Glucose-Dependent Insulinotropic Polypeptide) sequence, heavily modified to also bind to the GLP-1 receptor.\n\nModifications: It contains two non-coded amino acid residues (alpha-aminoisobutyric acid) at positions 2 and 13 to protect it from degradation by the DPP-4 enzyme.\n\nAcylation: It is acylated at a lysine residue with a C20 fatty diacid moiety. This fatty acid chain binds tightly to albumin in the blood, preventing renal clearance and extending its half-life to approximately 5 days (116 hours), allowing for once-weekly dosing.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\nTirzepatide is an 'imbalanced' dual agonist. It has a much higher affinity for the GIP receptor (comparable to native GIP) than for the GLP-1 receptor (about 5 times weaker than native GLP-1). This imbalance is the secret to its success.\n\n1. GLP-1 Action: Activation of the GLP-1 receptor stimulates glucose-dependent insulin secretion, inhibits glucagon release, promotes satiety, and delays gastric emptying.\n\n2. GIP Action: GIP is the primary incretin hormone. Activation enhances the insulinotropic effect of GLP-1. GIP receptors in white adipose tissue promote lipid buffering, increasing insulin sensitivity. GIP also acts in the brain to further suppress appetite and acts as an anti-emetic (which is why Tirzepatide causes less nausea than pure GLP-1 agonists).\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\n- SURMOUNT-1: 22.5% weight loss at highest dose (15 mg) over 72 weeks\n- SURMOUNT-2 (T2DM): 14.7% weight loss\n- 36% of participants on 15 mg achieved 25%+ weight loss\n\nThe next generation of these drugs (like Retatrutide) adds a third agonist: Glucagon. While GLP-1 and GIP reduce appetite, Glucagon actively increases energy expenditure (basal metabolic rate).\n\nLong-Term Use Data: Tirzepatide is designed for chronic, long-term use. Clinical data shows that if the drug is stopped, patients regain the majority of the lost weight within a year.",
