            deepDive: "SS-31 (D-Arg-dimethylTyr-Lys-Phe-NH2) is a cell-permeable, mitochondria-targeted tetrapeptide discovered by Dr. Hazel Szeto and Dr. Peter Schiller (hence the 'SS').\n\nTargeting: Unlike most drugs that distribute randomly throughout the cell, SS-31 is highly concentrated in the inner mitochondrial membrane (IMM). It achieves this concentration (>1000-fold compared to the cytosol) due to its alternating aromatic and basic amino acid residues.\n\nPharmacokinetics: Following subcutaneous injection, it has an elimination half-life of approximately 2 to 4 hours, but its structural repair effects on the mitochondria persist.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\nSS-31's primary mechanism of action is its interaction with cardiolipin.\n\n1. Cardiolipin Binding: Cardiolipin is a unique phospholipid found exclusively in the inner mitochondrial membrane. It is essential for the optimal function of the electron transport chain (ETC) complexes. During aging or disease, cardiolipin undergoes peroxidation (damage by free radicals), causing the ETC complexes to destabilize and leak more reactive oxygen species (ROS).\n\n2. Cytochrome C Interaction: SS-31 selectively binds to cardiolipin via electrostatic and hydrophobic interactions. This binding protects cardiolipin from peroxidation and stabilizes its interaction with cytochrome c.\n\n3. Restoring Electron Flow: By stabilizing the cardiolipin-cytochrome c complex, SS-31 restores efficient electron transfer, drastically reducing the leakage of ROS and restoring the production of ATP.\n\n4. Not a Traditional Antioxidant: SS-31 does not scavenge existing free radicals. Instead, it prevents their production at the source by fixing the structural integrity of the electron transport chain.\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\n- Barth Syndrome: Granted Fast Track and Orphan Drug designations. While it showed promise in early trials, it failed to meet its primary endpoints in a Phase 3 trial.\n- Primary Mitochondrial Myopathy (PMM): In a randomized trial (MMPOWER), Elamipretide significantly increased the distance patients could walk in 6 minutes.\n- Heart Failure & Ischemia: Extensive animal models show SS-31 protects the heart and kidneys from ischemia-reperfusion injury.\n\nLong-Term Use Data: Clinical trials have administered Elamipretide daily for up to 12 months with an excellent safety profile.",
