            costInfo: "Research Chemical Vendors: ~$30-$50 per 2mg vial.",
            comparisons: [
                CompoundComparison(feature: "Primary Target", values: ["PEG-MGF": "Muscle Stem Cells (Satellite Cells)", "IGF-1 LR3": "Mature Muscle Cells", "BPC-157": "Tendons, Ligaments, Gut"]),
                CompoundComparison(feature: "Action", values: ["PEG-MGF": "Proliferation (Waking up cells)", "IGF-1 LR3": "Differentiation (Maturing cells)", "BPC-157": "Angiogenesis (New blood vessels)"]),
                CompoundComparison(feature: "Half-life", values: ["PEG-MGF": "48-72 hours", "IGF-1 LR3": "20-30 hours", "BPC-157": "4-6 hours"]),
                CompoundComparison(feature: "Best Time to Take", values: ["PEG-MGF": "Rest Days", "IGF-1 LR3": "Workout Days", "BPC-157": "Daily"]),
            ],
            deepDive: "Mechano Growth Factor (MGF) is an alternative splice variant of the Insulin-like Growth Factor-1 (IGF-1) gene. It is officially known as IGF-1 Ec in humans.\n\nThe Splice Variant: When a muscle is subjected to mechanical overload, the IGF-1 gene is spliced to produce MGF. MGF contains the standard IGF-1 sequence but has a unique C-terminal extension (the E domain) that gives it entirely different biological properties than systemic IGF-1.\n\nThe PEGylation: Native MGF is highly susceptible to enzymatic degradation, with a half-life of only 5 to 7 minutes. PEGylation shields the peptide from proteases and prevents rapid renal clearance, extending the half-life to 48-72 hours without altering the peptide's binding affinity.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\n1. Satellite Cell Proliferation: The primary role of MGF is to stimulate the proliferation (multiplication) of mononucleated myoblasts (satellite cells). These are the dormant stem cells located between the basal lamina and sarcolemma of muscle fibers.\n\n2. The Two-Phase Repair Process:\n- Phase 1 (Proliferation): Immediately after damage, MGF is expressed. It wakes up satellite cells and causes them to multiply.\n- Phase 2 (Differentiation): A day or two later, MGF levels drop, and systemic IGF-1 levels rise. IGF-1 signals those newly multiplied satellite cells to differentiate (mature) and fuse with the damaged muscle fiber.\n\n3. The Timing Conflict: If you inject exogenous IGF-1 at the same time as MGF, the IGF-1 will force the satellite cells to differentiate before they have had a chance to multiply. This is why PEG-MGF must be administered during the proliferation phase (rest days), and IGF-1 during the differentiation phase.\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\n- Muscular Dystrophy & Sarcopenia: In animal models, MGF injections have been shown to significantly increase muscle mass and prevent apoptosis in diseased muscle tissue.\n- Neuroprotection: MGF is also expressed in the brain following ischemia (stroke). Studies have shown that MGF has potent neuroprotective effects, preventing the death of motor neurons.\n\nLong-Term Use Data: Because it forces stem cell proliferation, chronic, uninterrupted use could theoretically exhaust the local satellite cell pool (stem cell depletion). Cycling (4 weeks on, 4 weeks off) is critical.",
            faq: [
                FAQItem(question: "Can I mix PEG-MGF and IGF-1 in the same syringe?", answer: "Absolutely NOT. Biologically, they compete with each other. If you inject them together, the IGF-1 will force the stem cells to mature before the MGF has a chance to make them multiply. You will ruin the effect of both peptides."),
                FAQItem(question: "Why do I get a red, itchy bump where I inject it?", answer: "This is a common reaction to the PEG (Polyethylene Glycol) molecule, not the MGF itself. It is usually a mild histamine reaction. Diluting the peptide with more bacteriostatic water or taking an over-the-counter antihistamine can help."),
                FAQItem(question: "Do I have to inject it directly into the muscle?", answer: "No. Because of the PEGylation, the peptide survives in the bloodstream for days. You can inject it subcutaneously (into belly fat), and it will circulate systemically, finding and binding to damaged muscle tissue anywhere in the body."),
                FAQItem(question: "Will it help heal a torn tendon?", answer: "Not directly. MGF is specific to muscle tissue (myoblasts). For tendon, ligament, or connective tissue repair, BPC-157 or TB-500 are the correct peptides to use."),
                FAQItem(question: "Is it safe for drug-tested athletes?", answer: "No. WADA explicitly bans all Growth Factors and their synthetic analogs, including MGF and PEG-MGF."),
