            costInfo: "Research Chemical Vendors: ~$100-$200 for a bottle of 60 capsules (50mg each).",
            comparisons: [
                CompoundComparison(feature: "Primary Target", values: ["5-Amino-1MQ": "NNMT Enzyme", "MOTS-c": "Mitochondria (AMPK)", "Tesamorelin": "Pituitary (GH Release)"]),
                CompoundComparison(feature: "Mechanism", values: ["5-Amino-1MQ": "NAD+ salvage, Fat burning", "MOTS-c": "Exercise mimetic", "Tesamorelin": "Visceral fat lipolysis"]),
                CompoundComparison(feature: "Administration", values: ["5-Amino-1MQ": "Oral", "MOTS-c": "SubQ Injection", "Tesamorelin": "SubQ Injection"]),
                CompoundComparison(feature: "Muscle Effect", values: ["5-Amino-1MQ": "Preserves/Builds", "MOTS-c": "Neutral", "Tesamorelin": "Preserves"]),
            ],
            deepDive: "5-Amino-1-methylquinolinium (5-Amino-1MQ) is a small, membrane-permeable molecule.\n\nDiscovery: It was discovered through high-throughput screening by researchers looking for selective inhibitors of the Nicotinamide N-methyltransferase (NNMT) enzyme.\n\nPharmacokinetics: It has excellent oral bioavailability. In murine models, it demonstrated a mean terminal elimination half-life of approximately 3.8 hours (IV) to 6.9 hours (oral), necessitating multiple daily doses to maintain steady-state inhibition.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\nThe mechanism revolves entirely around the salvage pathway of NAD+ (Nicotinamide Adenine Dinucleotide).\n\n1. The NNMT Problem: NNMT is an enzyme highly expressed in white adipose tissue (fat cells) and the liver. Its job is to take Nicotinamide (NAM) and attach a methyl group to it, creating 1-methylnicotinamide (1-MNA). This reaction consumes a methyl group from SAMe.\n\n2. The NAD+ Drain: Nicotinamide (NAM) is supposed to be recycled back into NAD+ via the salvage pathway. When NNMT is overactive (as it is in obesity and aging), it permanently removes NAM from the salvage pathway, leading to a massive depletion of cellular NAD+.\n\n3. The Solution: 5-Amino-1MQ is a highly selective, substrate site-targeting inhibitor of NNMT (IC50 = 1.2 \u{03BC}M). By blocking NNMT, it prevents the methylation of NAM.\n\n4. The Result: NAM is forced back into the salvage pathway, leading to a dramatic increase in intracellular NAD+ levels. Elevated NAD+ activates Sirtuin-1 (SIRT1), which in turn increases cellular metabolism, mitochondrial biogenesis, and lipid oxidation (fat burning).\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\n- Animal Models: In a landmark 2018 study (Neelakantan et al.), diet-induced obese mice treated with 5-Amino-1MQ showed a 30% reduction in body weight and a 40% reduction in fat mass over 11 days, without any change in food intake.\n- Muscle Hypertrophy: The same study noted that the treated mice actually had larger muscle fibers than the control group.\n- Human Data: There are currently no published, peer-reviewed human clinical trials for 5-Amino-1MQ.\n\nMethylation Balance: Because NNMT consumes methyl groups, inhibiting it leaves more methyl groups available in the body. Individuals with specific genetic mutations (like COMT or MTHFR) should be aware that altering methyl group availability can have widespread systemic effects.\n\nLong-Term Use Data: Due to the lack of human trials, long-term safety is unknown. The primary theoretical concern with chronic, uncycled use is the disruption of the body's natural methylation homeostasis.",
            faq: [
                FAQItem(question: "Is 5-Amino-1MQ a peptide?", answer: "No. Peptides are chains of amino acids. 5-Amino-1MQ is a small molecule (a quinoline derivative). It is grouped with peptides simply because it is sold by the same research chemical companies and used by the same community."),
                FAQItem(question: "Do I have to inject it?", answer: "No. Because it is a small molecule, it easily survives the digestive tract and is highly bioavailable when taken orally in capsule form."),
                FAQItem(question: "Will it make me lose weight if I eat a terrible diet?", answer: "In mice, it caused weight loss without a change in diet. In humans, anecdotal reports suggest it will prevent weight gain on a bad diet, but you still need a moderate caloric deficit to see significant, rapid fat loss."),
                FAQItem(question: "Why do I need to take breaks (cycle it)?", answer: "NNMT is a natural enzyme that your body uses to regulate methylation. Permanently turning it off for months or years could lead to an imbalance in your methyl donors (like SAMe), which are needed for neurotransmitter production and DNA repair. 4-8 weeks on, 4 weeks off is the safest approach."),
                FAQItem(question: "Can I take it with NMN or NAD+ supplements?", answer: "Yes, this is highly recommended. NMN gives your body the raw materials to make NAD+, and 5-Amino-1MQ stops your fat cells from destroying that NAD+. They work perfectly together."),
