            deepDive: "Tesofensine (NS2330) is a novel, centrally acting triple monoamine reuptake inhibitor (SNDRI).\n\nDevelopment: Originally developed by NeuroSearch (a Danish biotech company) for Parkinson's and Alzheimer's. The weight loss side effect was so profound they pivoted to obesity trials.\n\nPharmacokinetics: It has excellent oral bioavailability. Its most notable feature is its exceptionally long terminal half-life of approximately 8 to 9 days in humans. This means it takes over a month to reach steady-state plasma concentrations, and over a month to fully clear the body after discontinuation.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\nTesofensine blocks the presynaptic reuptake transporters for three neurotransmitters:\n\n1. Dopamine (DAT): Inhibition in the striatum and nucleus accumbens enhances the reward pathway, reducing hedonic eating and providing motivation and well-being.\n\n2. Serotonin (SERT): Inhibition in the hypothalamus directly stimulates POMC/CART neurons, the primary drivers of satiety.\n\n3. Norepinephrine (NET): Inhibition increases sympathetic nervous system tone, directly increasing resting energy expenditure (thermogenesis) and stimulating lipolysis.\n\nClinical Trial Summary (TIPO-1):\nIn a 24-week, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial published in The Lancet, 203 obese patients were given either placebo, 0.25mg, 0.5mg, or 1.0mg of Tesofensine.\n- Placebo: lost 2.2 kg\n- 0.25mg: lost 6.7 kg\n- 0.5mg: lost 11.3 kg\n- 1.0mg: lost 12.8 kg\nThe 1.0mg dose caused significant increases in heart rate and blood pressure. The 0.5mg dose produced massive weight loss (~10% body weight) with a manageable side effect profile.\n\nRecent studies (2023) suggest Tesofensine's profound appetite suppression is also mediated by silencing GABAergic neurons in the lateral hypothalamus, a novel mechanism that separates it from older stimulants like Phentermine.",
            faq: [
                FAQItem(question: "Is Tesofensine a peptide?", answer: "No. It is a small molecule synthetic drug. It is grouped with peptides because it is sold by the same research chemical companies and used by the biohacking community for weight loss."),
                FAQItem(question: "Is it like Adderall or Phentermine?", answer: "It is similar in that it increases dopamine and norepinephrine, giving you energy and suppressing appetite. However, because it also increases serotonin, it provides a much 'smoother' feeling of well-being and satiety, without the harsh, jittery crash associated with amphetamines."),
                FAQItem(question: "Why is the long half-life a problem?", answer: "A half-life of 8 days means the drug builds up in your system. If you take 0.5mg every day, by week 4, you have a much higher concentration in your blood than you did in week 1. If you suddenly experience severe insomnia or a racing heart, stopping the drug won't fix the problem immediately; it will take weeks to leave your system."),
                FAQItem(question: "Can I take it with my antidepressant?", answer: "Absolutely NOT. Combining Tesofensine with an SSRI (like Lexapro, Zoloft, Prozac) or an SNRI can cause Serotonin Syndrome, a potentially fatal condition characterized by high fever, seizures, and irregular heartbeat."),
                FAQItem(question: "Will it make me lose muscle?", answer: "Like any drug that causes a massive caloric deficit, you will lose muscle if you do not eat enough protein and lift weights. However, the stimulant effect of Tesofensine often helps users maintain high training intensity, which helps preserve muscle."),
