            deepDive: "Mecasermin (Increlex) is a recombinant DNA-derived human insulin-like growth factor-1 (rhIGF-1). It contains 70 amino acids in a single chain with three intramolecular disulfide bridges, identical to the endogenous human IGF-1 sequence.\n\nPharmacokinetics: In the human body, 99% of IGF-1 is bound to IGF-binding proteins (primarily IGFBP-3) and the Acid-Labile Subunit (ALS). This ternary complex extends the half-life of native IGF-1 to roughly 15-20 hours. However, when exogenous rhIGF-1 is injected, it must find available binding proteins. The functional half-life of an Increlex injection is approximately 5.8 hours.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\n1. Receptor Activation: Mecasermin binds to the Type 1 IGF receptor (IGF-1R), which is homologous to the insulin receptor.\n2. Metabolic Actions (Insulin-like): Because it can bind to both the IGF-1 receptor and the insulin receptor (though with lower affinity), it exerts potent hypoglycemic effects. It suppresses hepatic glucose production and stimulates peripheral glucose utilization.\n3. Mitogenic Actions (Growth): It activates the PI3K/Akt and MAPK pathways, stimulating DNA synthesis, cell proliferation, and inhibiting apoptosis. In children with open epiphyses, it stimulates linear bone growth. In adults, it stimulates muscle hypertrophy and hyperplasia.\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\nIncrelex was approved based on clinical trials involving children with severe primary IGF-1 deficiency (Laron syndrome). Children treated with mecasermin grew an average of 8.0 cm in the first year, compared to a pre-treatment growth rate of 2.8 cm/year.\n\nThe Iplex Failure: A competing drug, Iplex (mecasermin rinfabate), combined rhIGF-1 with rhIGFBP-3 to extend the half-life and reduce hypoglycemia. However, due to patent disputes, Iplex was pulled from the market.\n\nThe Binding Protein Bottleneck: Because native IGF-1 relies on IGFBP-3 to remain stable in the blood, injecting massive doses can saturate the available binding proteins. The excess 'free' IGF-1 is rapidly cleared by the kidneys and causes acute, severe hypoglycemia. This is why the LR3 and DES variants were created — to evade the binding proteins entirely.",
            faq: [
                FAQItem(question: "Can I buy real Increlex from a peptide website?", answer: "Almost certainly not. Real Increlex is a tightly controlled, incredibly expensive pharmaceutical liquid. If a website is selling 'Native IGF-1' as a $40 lyophilized powder, it is likely fake, or it is actually LR3."),
                FAQItem(question: "Why do bodybuilders use LR3 instead of Native IGF-1?", answer: "Three reasons: 1) Cost. LR3 is cheap; Increlex is thousands of dollars. 2) Half-life. LR3 lasts 24 hours; Native lasts 6 hours. 3) Potency. LR3 doesn't bind to binding proteins, making it functionally stronger milligram-for-milligram."),
                FAQItem(question: "If I take this, will I grow taller?", answer: "Only if your growth plates (epiphyses) are still open (usually closes between ages 16-21). If you are an adult, it will not make you taller; it will only make your muscles, organs, and bones thicker (acromegaly)."),
                FAQItem(question: "How fast does the blood sugar drop happen?", answer: "Very fast. The Tmax (time to maximum concentration in the blood) is roughly 2 hours, but the hypoglycemic effects can begin within 30 minutes of injection. You must eat immediately."),
                FAQItem(question: "Is it safer than insulin?", answer: "Marginally, but they are both incredibly dangerous if misused. An overdose of either can lead to a hypoglycemic coma and death."),
            ],
