            deepDive: "YK-11 ((17\u{03B1},20E)-17,20-[(1-methoxyethylidene)bis(oxy)]-3-oxo-19-norpregna-4,20-diene-21-carboxylic acid methyl ester) was first described in 2011 by Japanese researcher Yuichiro Kanno.\n\nThe Steroid Structure: Despite being marketed as a SARM, YK-11 has the exact four-ring steroidal backbone of a DHT (dihydrotestosterone) derivative. It is structurally very similar to the anabolic steroid Norethindrone. The methylated 17\u{03B1} position indicates oral bioavailability and hepatotoxicity.\n\nPharmacokinetics: Because it has never been studied in humans or animals, its exact half-life and metabolic pathways are unknown. Based on its steroidal structure and user reports of dosing frequency, the half-life is estimated at 6-12 hours.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\n1. Partial Agonism: YK-11 binds to the Androgen Receptor (AR). However, in vitro studies show it is only a partial agonist. It does not induce the full N/C interaction (the folding of the receptor) that full agonists like DHT do.\n\n2. The Follistatin Secretion: This is where YK-11 is unique. When YK-11 binds to the AR in C2C12 myoblasts (muscle cells), it induces the expression of Follistatin (FST) to a much greater degree than DHT.\n\n3. The Myostatin Blockade: The locally produced Follistatin then binds to and neutralizes Myostatin, removing the negative regulator of muscle growth. Therefore, YK-11 exerts anabolic effects through two distinct pathways: direct AR stimulation and indirect Myostatin inhibition.\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\nZERO In Vivo Data: There are absolutely no published animal (mouse/rat) or human clinical trials on YK-11. All data regarding its mechanism of action comes from in vitro (petri dish) cellular assays performed by Kanno et al. between 2011 and 2013. Because it has never been tested in a living organism by scientists, its true toxicity, optimal dosage, and long-term effects are entirely based on anecdotal reports from the biohacking community.\n\nSynergy & Antagonism Analysis:\nReceptor Competition: Because YK-11 is a partial agonist, if you stack it with a full agonist (like Testosterone or RAD-140), YK-11 will actually compete for the receptor and potentially weaken the direct androgenic effect of the stronger drug, while still providing the Follistatin boost.\n\nLong-Term Use Data: Unknown. However, based on its steroidal structure, long-term use would undoubtedly lead to severe hepatotoxicity, dyslipidemia, and permanent hypogonadism (HPTA shutdown).",
            faq: [
                FAQItem(question: "Is YK-11 a SARM or a Steroid?", answer: "Chemically, it is a synthetic steroid (a DHT derivative). It is marketed as a SARM because it was discovered during the SARM boom and is sold by SARM companies, but its molecular structure is steroidal."),
                FAQItem(question: "Do I really need a PCT for this?", answer: "YES. YK-11 is highly suppressive. If you do not run a PCT (like Enclomiphene or Nolvadex), your testosterone levels will remain crashed for months, you will lose all the muscle you gained, and you will feel terrible."),
                FAQItem(question: "Why do my joints hurt so much on YK-11?", answer: "As a DHT derivative, YK-11 does not aromatize into estrogen. Estrogen is required for joint lubrication and water retention. By crushing your natural testosterone (and therefore your estrogen), your joints become completely dry."),
                FAQItem(question: "Can I take it if I'm trying to lose fat?", answer: "Yes. Because it builds dry muscle and does not cause water retention, it is highly effective in a caloric deficit to preserve muscle mass while cutting fat."),
