            deepDive: "Follistatin is an autocrine glycoprotein that is expressed in nearly all tissues. It is encoded by the FST gene. Alternative splicing of the mRNA results in two main isoforms: FS-315 (the systemic, circulating form) and FS-288 (the tissue-bound form).\n\nThe 344 Variant: Follistatin 344 is the precursor protein. When the 29-amino acid signal peptide is cleaved off, it becomes the mature FS-315. In the research chemical market, 'FS-344' is the standard nomenclature.\n\nPharmacokinetics: As a recombinant peptide, FS-344 has a very poor pharmacokinetic profile. Its serum half-life is estimated to be between 1 and 2 hours. This rapid clearance is why pharmaceutical companies abandoned the injectable peptide in favor of gene therapy vectors (AAV).\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\n1. The TGF-β Superfamily: Myostatin (GDF-8) and Activin are members of the transforming growth factor-beta (TGF-β) superfamily. They bind to the Activin type IIB receptor (ActRIIB) on muscle cells, triggering a Smad2/3 signaling cascade that inhibits the Akt/mTOR pathway, effectively halting muscle protein synthesis.\n\n2. The Decoy: Follistatin acts as a highly potent, irreversible binding protein (a decoy). It physically wraps around Myostatin and Activin in the bloodstream, preventing them from ever reaching or binding to the ActRIIB receptor.\n\n3. The Result: By neutralizing Myostatin, the Smad2/3 inhibition is lifted. The Akt/mTOR pathway is disinhibited, leading to massive, unchecked muscle hypertrophy and hyperplasia.\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\nGene Therapy (AAV1-FS344): Dr. Brian Kaspar's research using Adeno-Associated Virus to deliver the FS-344 gene into muscles of macaques achieved massive, permanent muscle growth. This led to human trials for Becker Muscular Dystrophy, showing significant improvements in muscle function.\n\nThe Activin Problem: Follistatin does not just block Myostatin; it also blocks Activin. Activin is crucial for regulating the reproductive system (specifically FSH). Chronic use can theoretically disrupt the HPTA axis and reproductive function, which is why cycles must be kept short.\n\nLong-Term Use Data: Animal models with chronic myostatin inhibition (like the famous 'Belgian Blue' cows) show that while muscle mass is massive, the animals often suffer from weakened connective tissue, reduced cardiovascular endurance, and metabolic abnormalities.",
            faq: [
                FAQItem(question: "Is this the same thing as the Follistatin Gene Therapy I read about?", answer: "NO. Gene therapy uses a virus to rewrite your DNA so your own body produces Follistatin for years. The peptide version sold online only lasts in your body for 2 hours and requires daily injections."),
                FAQItem(question: "Why do people say it causes tendon tears?", answer: "Myostatin inhibition causes your muscle fibers to grow incredibly fast. Tendons and ligaments grow very slowly. If your chest gets 20% stronger in 3 weeks, your tendons haven't adapted yet. When you try to bench press that new heavy weight, the muscle can handle it, but the tendon snaps."),
                FAQItem(question: "If the half-life is only 2 hours, why does it work?", answer: "Even a 2-hour window of zero myostatin allows the mTOR pathway to surge, triggering a cascade of protein synthesis that lasts for hours after the peptide is gone. However, this is why it must be injected daily."),
