            deepDive: "L-Carnitine (β-hydroxy-γ-N-trimethylaminobutyric acid) is synthesized in the liver and kidneys from the essential amino acids lysine and methionine.\n\nPharmacokinetics: Oral L-Carnitine is absorbed via active transport (OCTN2) in the small intestine. Because this transporter is easily saturated, oral bioavailability is extremely low (5-15%). Unabsorbed L-Carnitine is metabolized by gut microbiota into trimethylamine (TMA), which the liver oxidizes into TMAO. Intramuscular injection bypasses the gut entirely, providing 100% bioavailability and zero TMAO conversion.\n\nMechanism Deep Dive:\n1. The Carnitine Shuttle: Long-chain fatty acids cannot cross the inner mitochondrial membrane on their own. CPT1 attaches the fatty acid to L-Carnitine, forming acylcarnitine.\n2. Translocation: The acylcarnitine complex is transported across the inner mitochondrial membrane by CACT.\n3. Beta-Oxidation: Inside the mitochondrial matrix, CPT2 detaches the L-Carnitine, freeing the fatty acid for beta-oxidation (burning for ATP).\n4. Androgen Receptor Upregulation: Kraemer et al. (2006) demonstrated that L-Carnitine L-Tartrate supplementation significantly increased androgen receptor density in skeletal muscle cells.\n\nClinical Trial Summary:\n- Wall et al. (2011) in the Journal of Physiology showed that when L-Carnitine is elevated in the muscle (via insulin loading), it spares muscle glycogen during low-intensity exercise and reduces lactate during high-intensity exercise, profoundly improving endurance.\n- L-Carnitine (2-4 g/day) has been successfully used to treat hyperthyroidism by preventing thyroid hormones from entering the cell nucleus.\n\nThe Insulin Requirement: The OCTN2 transporter that pulls L-Carnitine from the blood into the muscle cell is insulin-dependent. Injecting L-Carnitine while in a strict fasted/keto state will result in the L-Carnitine floating in the blood and eventually being excreted. It must be accompanied by an insulin spike (carbohydrates) to actually load the muscle.",
